VALUES
(43, 6, 1, 41, 6, 31, 44, 'sea of Galilee', 'Jesus'' Compassion and Provision', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement across the sea and his compassion for the people. In John, Jesus goes over the sea of Galilee, while in Mark, he responds to the crowd''s needs after arriving in a desert place. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus providing for those who seek him.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 1, 43, 6, 23, 23, 'the sea of Tiberias', 'Connection of Tiberias References', 'Both passages emphasize Tiberias as a location related to Jesus'' ministry. The mention of Tiberias in both verses connects the geographical setting of Jesus'' actions and the subsequent events involving the feeding of the multitude.', 'keyword', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 1, 42, 5, 1, 1, 'sea of Galilee', 'Connection of Geographical Locations', 'Both passages refer to bodies of water associated with Jesus'' ministry. John mentions the ''sea of Galilee,'' while Luke refers to the ''lake of Gennesaret,'' which is another name for the same body of water.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 1, 4, 34, 11, 11, 'sea of Galilee', 'Geographical Connection of Borders', 'Both passages emphasize geographical locations related to bodies of water. John 6:1 mentions the sea of Galilee, while Numbers 34:11 refers to the sea of Chinnereth, which is another name for the same body of water.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 1, 40, 4, 18, 18, 'sea of Galilee', 'Connection through Sea of Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize the Sea of Galilee as a significant location in Jesus'' ministry. In John, Jesus is noted to be ''over the sea of Galilee,'' while in Matthew, he is seen walking by the same sea, highlighting its importance in his early interactions with his disciples.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 1, 43, 21, 1, 1, 'sea of Tiberias', 'Connection at the Sea of Tiberias', 'Both passages emphasize the location ''sea of Tiberias,'' linking Jesus'' actions in different contexts. This connection highlights the significance of this location in the narrative.', 'keyword', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 1, 40, 14, 13, 21, 'went over the sea of Galilee', 'Jesus'' Compassion and Provision', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement across water and his compassion for the crowds. In John 6:1, Jesus goes over the sea, leading to the events in Matthew 14:13-21 where he provides for the multitude. This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' ministry and miraculous acts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 2, 40, 4, 24, 25, 'miracles which he did on them that were diseased', 'Miracles and Multitudes', 'Both passages emphasize the great multitude that followed Jesus due to his healing miracles. The SOURCE verse highlights the miracles performed on the diseased, while the TARGET passage details the sick people brought to him for healing, illustrating the impact of his miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 2, 40, 12, 15, 15, NULL, 'Healing and Multitudes Following Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the great multitudes that followed Jesus due to his healing miracles. They highlight the response of the crowds to Jesus'' miraculous works, showcasing his ability to attract large groups seeking healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 2, 40, 15, 30, 31, 'because they saw his miracles', 'Healing Miracles and Multitudes', 'Both passages emphasize the great multitude that followed Jesus due to his healing miracles. The SOURCE verse mentions the multitude following him because of the miracles, while the TARGET passage describes the multitudes bringing the sick to Jesus for healing, showcasing the impact of his miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 2, 41, 6, 33, 33, 'great multitude followed him', 'Crowds Following Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the large crowds that followed Jesus due to his miracles and teachings. The multitude''s eagerness to seek him highlights their recognition of his significance.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 2, 43, 2, 11, 11, 'miracles which he did', 'Connection of Miracles and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the role of miracles in revealing Jesus'' glory and fostering belief among his followers. The multitude in John 6:2 follows Jesus due to the miracles he performed, while John 2:11 highlights the significance of his first miracle in strengthening the disciples'' faith.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 2, 40, 8, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Multitudes Following Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of great multitudes following Jesus. In John 6:2, the multitude is drawn by his miracles, while in Matthew 8:1, they follow him after he comes down from the mountain.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 3, 43, 6, 15, 15, 'into a mountain', 'Jesus Retreats to the Mountain', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement to a mountain, indicating a place of solitude and reflection. The first passage shows him sitting with his disciples, while the second highlights his departure to the mountain alone in response to the crowd''s intentions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 3, 42, 9, 28, 28, 'went up into a mountain', 'Mountain Prayer Connection', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus going up into a mountain, highlighting a significant moment of communion with his disciples and prayer. This connection illustrates the importance of the mountain setting in Jesus'' ministry.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 3, 40, 14, 23, 23, 'went up into a mountain', 'Jesus in the Mountain', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus going up into a mountain, highlighting a moment of separation from the crowd. This setting serves as a backdrop for significant spiritual activities, such as teaching and prayer.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 3, 40, 15, 29, 29, NULL, 'Jesus Sitting on a Mountain', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus going up into a mountain and sitting down. This parallel highlights a consistent setting in Jesus'' ministry where he teaches or interacts with his disciples.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 3, 42, 6, 12, 13, 'into a mountain', 'Jesus and His Disciples', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus going up into a mountain with his disciples. This connection highlights the significance of the mountain setting for important moments in Jesus'' ministry, including prayer and the selection of the apostles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 4, 43, 2, 13, 13, 'the passover, a feast of the Jews', 'Passover References in John', 'Both passages emphasize the proximity of the Passover, indicating its significance in the narrative. The mention of the Passover in both verses connects the events surrounding Jesus'' actions in Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 4, 43, 11, 55, 55, 'the passover, a feast of the Jews', 'Connection of Passover References', 'Both passages emphasize the proximity of the Passover, indicating its significance in the Jewish calendar. The mention of the Passover in both contexts highlights the communal preparations and spiritual significance associated with this feast.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 4, 5, 16, 1, 1, 'the passover, a feast of the Jews', 'Passover Observance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Passover, with John noting its proximity and Deuteronomy instructing its observance. This connection highlights the continuity of the Passover celebration in Jewish tradition.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 4, 2, 12, 6, 14, 'the passover, a feast of the Jews', 'Passover Significance Connection', 'This connection highlights the significance of the Passover in both passages. John 6:4 mentions the Passover, while Exodus 12:6-14 details its observance and the protective power of the blood during the original Passover event.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 4, 3, 23, 5, 5, 'the passover, a feast of the Jews', 'Connection of Passover References', 'This connection highlights the significance of Passover in both passages. John 6:4 mentions the approaching Passover, while Leviticus 23:5 specifies the timing of the Lord''s Passover.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 5, 40, 15, 33, 33, 'Whence shall we buy bread', 'Feeding the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the question of sourcing bread for a large crowd. They highlight the disciples'' concern about feeding a multitude in a wilderness setting.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 5, 42, 9, 12, 13, 'that these may eat', 'Feeding the Multitude Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the need for food for a large crowd. In John, Jesus asks Philip about buying bread, while in Luke, the disciples express concern about feeding the multitude in a desert place.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 5, 40, 14, 14, 15, 'great company come unto him', 'Compassion and Provision for the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' awareness of a great multitude and his concern for their needs. In John, he specifically asks Philip about buying bread, while in Matthew, he is moved with compassion and addresses the disciples'' concern for food.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 5, 43, 1, 43, 43, 'Philip', 'Connection through Philip''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize Philip''s involvement in Jesus'' ministry. In John 1:43, Jesus calls Philip to follow him, while in John 6:5, Jesus specifically addresses Philip regarding the needs of the crowd.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 5, 43, 4, 35, 35, NULL, 'Connection of Harvest Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of lifting up one''s eyes to recognize a need or opportunity. In John 6:5, Jesus looks to Philip to address the crowd''s hunger, while in John 4:35, He encourages looking at the fields ready for harvest.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 5, 41, 6, 34, 35, 'these may eat', 'Compassion for the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' awareness of the crowd''s needs. In John, Jesus asks about feeding the people, while in Mark, he is moved with compassion for them. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' concern for those who are spiritually and physically hungry.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 5, 41, 8, 2, 4, 'Whence shall we buy bread', 'Compassion for the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' concern for the crowd''s hunger. In John, Jesus asks Philip about buying bread, while in Mark, he expresses compassion for the multitude who have been with him for three days without food.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 6, 1, 22, 1, 1, NULL, 'Testing of Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of testing faith in both passages. In John 6:6, Jesus tests Philip''s faith, while in Genesis 22:1, God tests Abraham''s obedience.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 6, 5, 13, 3, 3, NULL, 'Testing Faith and Loyalty', 'This connection highlights the theme of God testing individuals to reveal their faithfulness. Both passages emphasize the idea of proving one''s love and commitment to God through challenges.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 6, 14, 32, 31, 31, 'to prove him', 'Testing of the Heart', 'This connection highlights the theme of testing one''s heart and intentions. Both passages emphasize the idea of being tried to reveal what is within, as seen in the phrases about proving and trying.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 6, 5, 8, 16, 16, NULL, 'Testing and Provision in Wilderness', 'This connection highlights the theme of testing and provision in both passages. John 6:6 mentions proving, while Deuteronomy 8:16 discusses how God tested the Israelites to do them good.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 6, 5, 33, 8, 8, 'to prove him', 'Testing and Proving Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of proving individuals in faith. Both passages emphasize the act of testing, with John referencing a direct test of faith and Deuteronomy recalling a historical test of the Levites.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 7, 4, 11, 21, 22, NULL, 'Provision and Sufficiency in Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning sufficiency in the face of large needs. Both Philip and Moses express doubt about the ability to provide enough food for a vast number of people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 7, 41, 6, 37, 37, 'two hundred pennyworth of bread', 'Connection of Bread and Cost', 'Both passages emphasize the cost of bread needed to feed the crowd. The mention of ''two hundred pennyworth of bread'' in both verses highlights a shared concern about providing sufficient food.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 7, 43, 12, 5, 5, 'two hundred pennyworth of bread', 'Connection of Monetary Values', 'Both passages emphasize monetary amounts related to food and charity. Philip mentions ''two hundred pennyworth'' for bread, while Judas questions the value of ''three hundred pence'' for ointment, highlighting the theme of resource allocation for the needy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 7, 12, 4, 43, 43, 'not sufficient for them', 'Provision for Many', 'Both passages emphasize the insufficiency of resources to feed a large crowd. In John 6:7, Philip notes that two hundred pennyworth of bread is not enough, while in 2 Kings 4:43, the servitor questions the adequacy of food for a hundred men. This connection highlights the miraculous provision that follows in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 7, 40, 18, 28, 28, 'pennyworth', 'Connection of Monetary Value', 'Both passages emphasize monetary amounts, with ''pennyworth'' in John and ''pence'' in Matthew. This connection highlights the theme of debt and provision in the context of financial transactions.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 8, 40, 4, 18, 18, 'Andrew, Simon Peter’s brother', 'Connection of Andrew and Peter', 'This connection highlights the relationship between Andrew and Peter, as both passages mention Andrew as Simon Peter''s brother. The mention of Andrew in John 6:8 reinforces his identity as a disciple and brother of Peter, who is introduced in Matthew 4:18.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 8, 43, 1, 40, 44, 'Andrew, Simon Peter’s brother', 'Andrew''s Role in Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize Andrew''s identity as Simon Peter''s brother and his role in bringing others to Jesus. In John 1:40-44, Andrew first finds Simon Peter, while in John 6:8, he is mentioned as a disciple, highlighting his ongoing involvement in the ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 9, 12, 4, 42, 44, 'five barley loaves', 'Miraculous Provision of Food', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous provision of food from limited resources. In each case, a small amount of barley is multiplied to feed a large group, demonstrating God''s ability to provide abundantly despite initial doubts.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 9, 40, 14, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Loaves and Fishes', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of five loaves and two fishes. This connection highlights the disciples'' acknowledgment of limited resources in the face of a large crowd.', 'parallel', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 9, 41, 6, 38, 38, 'five barley loaves, and two small fishes', 'Connection of Loaves and Fishes', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''five loaves'' and ''two fishes'' as the resources available for feeding a large crowd. This connection highlights the miraculous nature of the feeding event in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 9, 42, 9, 13, 13, NULL, 'Feeding the Multitude Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''five loaves and two fishes'' as insufficient for the large crowd. This connection highlights the miraculous nature of the feeding events in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 9, 19, 78, 19, 19, NULL, 'Provision in the Wilderness', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s ability to provide sustenance in seemingly impossible situations. In both passages, there is a questioning of God''s provision, with the lad''s meager food and the inquiry about a table in the wilderness reflecting doubt in divine sustenance.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 9, 40, 16, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Loaves and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the significance of the ''five loaves'' in both passages. In John, the lad''s offering is questioned, while in Matthew, the disciples are reminded of the miracle involving the same loaves, emphasizing their lack of understanding.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 9, 41, 8, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Feeding Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous feeding of large crowds using limited resources. The mention of ''five loaves'' in both verses highlights the significance of the number in the context of abundance from scarcity.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 10, 42, 9, 14, 16, NULL, 'Feeding the Five Thousand', 'Both passages emphasize the number of men present, about five thousand, and the command to make them sit down. This connection highlights the miraculous feeding event that is central to both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 10, 40, 14, 18, 19, NULL, 'Feeding the Multitude Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the command to have the multitude sit down on the grass before the miracle of feeding occurs. This connection highlights the organization of the crowd and the setting for Jesus'' miraculous provision.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 10, 40, 15, 35, 36, 'Make the men sit down', 'Feeding the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the command to ''sit down'' before the miraculous feeding occurs. This connection highlights the organization of the crowd in preparation for the distribution of food.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 10, 41, 6, 39, 41, 'Make the men sit down', 'Feeding the Five Thousand', 'Both passages emphasize the command to make the men sit down, highlighting the organization of the crowd before the miracle of feeding. The mention of ''green grass'' in both accounts further connects the setting of this miraculous event.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 10, 41, 8, 6, 7, 'Make the men sit down', 'Feeding the Multitude', 'This connection highlights the act of Jesus commanding the people to sit down before performing a miracle of feeding. Both passages emphasize the organization of the crowd and the miraculous provision of food.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 11, 43, 6, 23, 23, 'given thanks', 'Connection of Thanksgiving in John', 'Both passages emphasize the act of giving thanks by Jesus. In John 6:11, Jesus gives thanks before distributing food, while John 6:23 references this act of thanksgiving in relation to the bread eaten.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 11, 52, 5, 18, 18, 'given thanks', 'Thankfulness in Action', 'This connection highlights the act of giving thanks in both passages. In John 6:11, Jesus gives thanks before distributing food, while 1 Thessalonians 5:18 emphasizes giving thanks in all circumstances.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 11, 40, 15, 36, 36, NULL, 'Miraculous Feeding of Multitudes', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus taking loaves and fishes, giving thanks, and distributing them through his disciples to the crowds. This connection highlights the miraculous nature of Jesus'' provision in feeding large groups of people.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 11, 45, 14, 6, 6, NULL, 'Thanksgiving in Eating', 'Both passages emphasize giving thanks while eating. In John 6:11, Jesus gives thanks before distributing food, while Romans 14:6 highlights that eating should be done with gratitude to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
